    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, sorry about that! My apologies, sometimes the thought process gets tangled up in the way the pieces fit together. I was trying to paint a picture for you, but I clearly let a little bit of the thought slip away. It was meant to illustrate the point about the transfer of risk.\n\nWhen I said \"like handing over a pile of things to a very nervous, tiny...\", I was trying to convey the idea that with FOB, the seller's job is done once the goods are physically on the ship. It’s a very precise moment, like a tiny, sharp-toothed goblin snatching the last piece of loot before running off.\n\nIn the world of shipping, think of it this way: FOB is like handing over a pile of things to a very nervous, tiny **goblin** who is immediately tasked with making sure they get onto the boat. The moment those goods are secured on the deck, the risk shifts to you.\n\nIf you were using CIF, the seller is the one who hires the big, lumbering ship and pays for the whole journey to Rotterdam, even though the risk still shifts at that initial loading point. It's all about who is holding the bag when things go sideways",
      "source": "target",
